<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-090-018 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 134 741</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Shopper  August 1991 v11 n8 p123(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>TelePad's mighty pen-based PC. (Telepad Corp.'s PowerPad notebookcomputer) (Trends andamp; Technology) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   TelePad Corp.a (Product introduction).andO;Product:   TelePad PowerPad (Portable computer) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionNotebook ComputersPen-Based I/O.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>When pen-based computer makers first began commercial production a few yearsago, their products were uniformly clunky, overpriced, and in need of astandard operating system to run everyday applications.andM;The industry still hasn't decided on a standard operating system forpen-based computers, but hardware inventors are forging ahead on most otherfronts.andP;  Indeed, clipboard-sized PCs are fast approaching the power andfunctionality levels that PC users have come to expect from conventionaldesktop machines.andM;A big splash will be heard in the pen-based PC world this November whenReston, Va.-based TelePad Corp. ships a new 5.5-pound 386SL system.andP;  Theproduct, called the PowerPad, includes 5Mb of RAM and a 20Mb or 40Mb harddrive.andP;  The computer (with a list price around $3,500) also features a fullarray of standard I/O ports, as well as VGA output.andM;By contrast, the more well-known GRiDPad from GRiD (a division of Tandy)weighs 4.5 pounds, but runs on a less powerful 80C86 chip and comes with just1Mb RAM.andM;TelePad is covering its bets by supporting both of the leading pen-basedoperating systems from Microsoft and Go Corp.andP;  (It also includes a version ofWindows from Pen Computing with its machine.)andM;A lot of hoopla has accompanied the arrival of pen-based computing.andP;  However,the impact of the PowerPad and similar products that find their way to marketis likely to be limited to technical and blue-collar niches.andP;  Neat?andP;  Yes.andO;But pen-based computing technology still has a long way to go before it setsthe world on fire.andO;</TEXT></DOC>